title: For Sale:  Colt Police Positive (Fitz)
postcontent: What we have is a Colt Police Positive 38 that has been modified in the Fitz (John Henry Fitzgerald (1870-1944)) style. NOTE: THIS IS NOT AN ACTUAL FITZ COLT. The condition is very good to very fine. The bluing is 95-100%.Although I don't know that is originl factory bluing. The gun will come with a Colt letter of authentication. Around 1926, Fitz began customizing both full size New Service, Police Positive, and Police Positive Special models to make them small concealed handguns, much like Colt’s then new Detective Special. This modification included shortening the barrel to two inches or less, fitting a new front sight, removing the hammer spur and carefully checkering the top of the now bobbed hammer, shortening the grip, and—unique to this type—cutting away the front 1/3 of the trigger guard and rounding off the now open edges. This trigger guard surgery left the bulk of the hammer exposed while carefully shrouding the very bottom and back of it to avoid snagging in the pocket. The open trigger guard allowed faster firing, accommodated large or gloved fingers, and according to some accounts made the weapon easier to fire through a pocket (if needed). While these modifications were done to large frame revolvers, they were performed mainly to the smaller Colt Detectives.  ########### NO TRADES PLEASE #############

This is not the flashlight that you are going to give to your kids to play with or your wife to keep in her purse! The SureFire M951 is designed to be used by professional soldiers and law-enforcement that operate in tactical situations.The Surefire M951 is designed to be used on Mil-Std 1913 Picatinny rail interface equipped shoulder-fired weapons. The flashlight is constructed from durable Mil-Spec hard anodized Aluminum (Mil-A-8625 Type III Class 2) and the rugged CNC machined housings are o-ring sealed for moisture and dust protection.This light is powered by 2 lithium batteries and comes with an incandescent bulb that produces a 65 lumen beam.Surefire flashlights are manufactured by Surefire LLC, which is based in Fountain Valley, California, U.S.A. Surefire produces a wide range of products that include flashlights, headlamps, weapon-mounted lights, laser sights, knives, sound suppressors, Picatinny Rails and batteries; and is a major supplier to the US Armed Forces and US Law-enforcement agencies."WHAT WE THINK ABOUT THE SUREFIRE M951This is a serious light – As we mentioned above, this flashlight is a serious piece of equipment and is not a toy. This is evidenced by the ITAR notice on this product, which means that it is not allowed to be exported outside the US without an export license issued by the U.S. Department of State, Office of Defense Trade Controls.It is made from military spec materials – Often flashlights these days are made from cheap plastic that won’t last very long. However this light is designed to be used in tough and dangerous situations and so is made from military spec materials.It has a good switch on/off system – The tail cap switch and tape switch operate independently of each other. When the tail cap switch is activated, the tape switch is disabled. Turning the tail cap switch to the off position activates the tape switch. The system disable feature eliminates the possibility of accidental activation from either switch.It could be brighter – The Surefire M951 comes with an incandescent bulb that produces a 65 lumen beam. 65 lumens is plenty of light, but for a serious tactical flashlight we would recommend upgrading the light to a brighter bulb. The light is compatible with an optional P61 high-output bulb can be used to produce a 120 lumen beam. Some users have also used other LED bulbs to produce an even brighter beam.It is not cheap – The Surefire M951 is not a cheap flashlight, with an MSRP of approximately $285. However, if you want a solid and serious flashlight for dangerous situations the price is not unreasonable for such a device at all. title: For Sale:  1924 Serbian Mauser
postcontent: RARE 1924 Serbian Mauser. In 1918 the State of Slovenes, Croats, and Serbs was merged with the Kingdom of Serbia to form the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes. In 1929 the state was renamed Yugoslavia.The first standardized rifle was the Model 1924. The first 100,000 rifles were built by Fabrique Nationale of Belgium. Machinery was bought, and by 1927 Mausers were being made in Serbia. Most model 1924's were re-arsenaled begining in 1947, under the Communist regime. Therefore, the more common Yugo 24/47 Mauser currently selling.This is a very nice non-modified 1924 "survivor". Beautiful stock and 90-95% blueing. All numbers match ( action, bolt, floor plate, stock, etc.) Very sharp bore. Soft leather sling. King Alexander cartouche on stock. 1930 manufacture date. NO IMPORT MARKINGS. title: For Sale/Trade:  Beautiful Marlin MR-7 W/Nice Glass
postcontent: Here is a rifle for sale/trade out of my collection that you hardly ever see available and most folks aren't familiar with. This is a beautiful 1998 "born on" date Marlin MR-7 chambered in 30-06. In almost like new condition with absolutely no flaws, it has a beautiful walnut checkered stock inlaid with the Marlin bullseye, 22" fully floated, crowned and recessed JM stamped barrel, almost flawless bluing, and a stunning jeweled bolt that was masterfully reworked by Skip Baldwin in Michigan. It is topped with a matching set of Leupold rings and bases and an awesome period correct Swift Model 656 3-9x40 scope. Here is a brief history of the rifle, which is touted as one of the finest and most accurate bolt rifles to ever be produced:The Marlin MR-7 was only made from 1996-1999. It was only chambered in .25-06, .270, .280, and .30-06. It features a 3-position safety, a bolt face encircled by three rings of 4140 steel, a shrouded striker and high-visibility cocking indicator. It has an adjustable 3-6 lb trigger, a forged, machined and heat-treated receiver and an extra-strong bolt lockup. The MR-7 has a hinged floorplate with a removable yet securely mounted 4-shot box magazine (The MR-7B does not). It has a 22" barrel with 6-groove precision rifling and a recessed muzzle. It also has a classically configured, cut-checkered American walnut stock. The later (1999) MR-7B was made with birch wood for the stock and the MR-7B didn't use a floorplate. It was a few $ cheaper and in 1999 the MR-7B was only available in .270 and .30-06 calibers.The Ring of steel around the cartridge and the strong locking lug bolt-face was mimicked off of the Remington 700.The wing-style safety was mimicked from the Winchester Model 70.The "Dogleg" Bolt handle mimicked the Ruger M77The floorplate with the detachable mag was mimicked from the Browning A-Bolt.This would be a special setup for someone's collection or a superb and accurate hunting setup. Also included in the deal is an extra factory box mag which is almost impossible to find available. Asking $650 sale/$700 trade, and I'll consider any nice firearm offers, especially a nice factory built AR or big bore wheelgun. Thanks for looking!
